. Blair's vision, grounded in a particular conception of social justice, is perhaps as challenging as the blueprint laid down by Beveridge. Ending child poverty presents Blair's Beveridge Lecture alongside the views of some of Britain's foremost policy analysts and commentators. This unique collection makes it possible to not only read the ideas of leading current thinkers in this critical area of policy, but also to compare them with the Prime Minister's lecture, and to see which ideas he himself took up and in what form. Ending child poverty is a record of not only the Lecture itself, but also of the ideas available to government and their influence on its leader at an important moment in the formation of policy. It provides a rich tapestry on analysis, insight and reflection that will, it is to be hoped, stimulate critical debate about the future shape of British welfare. This collection is essential reading for anyone interested in the future of modern society and politics and provides an accessible handbook for undergraduate students of politics, social policy and sociology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aPovertyzGreat Britain. 0aPublic welfarezGreat Britain. 0aSocial justicezGreat Britain. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Policy.2bisacsh1 aAtkinson, Tony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlair, Tony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButler, Lord, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCross, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeacon, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiddens, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGolding, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabul